I'd like to update my validators hotkey and coldkey mnemonics to something else. Is it possible whilst the validators still running?

It's not possible to change the mnemonic of a key -- however it is possible to change the hotkey itself (create a new one) -- would need to register the new hotkey first, once registered should be able to switch to it with minimal effect...

that's when switching hotkeys on the same coldkey.... if wanting a new coldkey, then would need to unstake the tao from the old hotkey to its parent coldkey... then do a transfer to the new coldkey... register a new hotkey under the new coldkey... stake the tao to the new hotkey and restart the validator with the new key combo...
That's what I was worried about. Generating another key. Esp when people above are getting 110mh/s now lol
Cheers
lol fun times
The biggest problem would be getting a new hotkey registered. How many GPUs do you need for it now
And how much time
difficulty seems to like a single direction over time ---> up
100 MH / s can take hours to days for a registration. if you want it registered in 1 -4 hours, would need more than 1 GH/s
the parameters are dependent on how many miners are contributing?
registration difficulty is dependent on how much hash is trying to register --the rate of UID turn-over on is kept relatively constant.

the reason for the curve is due to this transformation on the loss 

```python
def scaling_law_loss_to_params(loss):
    r""" (OpenAI scaling laws) Kaplan, Jared, et al. "c" arXiv:2001.08361 (2020)
    """
    num_params = torch.exp(torch.log(torch.tensor(8.8e13).to(loss.device)) -
                           torch.log(torch.clamp(loss, 1.69)) / 0.076)  # loss lower bound 1.69 is entropy of natural text
    return num_params

```

Hey @Rover [τ, τ] 

The initial 100 validator number is just that: an initial number. As everyone in this community has observed, the network can get rather unwieldy. If we just let it grow exponentially on its own without supervision, it will get even more messy. In fact the smallest unplanned change can have the most adverse effect on everyone (we've all seen this in the last couple of months). Finney is new, more complicated, and significantly larger than Nakamoto. Hence why we are starting off small and growing as we confirm things are running smoothly and correctly. 

As for funding -- the foundation is a non profit that is also the sole maintainer of the codebase (hopefully this changes in the future when more folks start contributing to the code). This means legally and ethically, we are limited in the way we make a profit and run the foundation. For example, if we started an AI service business on top of bittensor, then this would create a bit of a conflict of interest as we hold the authority keys, so this wouldn't be fair to everyone else. On the other hand if we just mined and did nothing else, then we would lose out on the delegation rewards and folks with big validators would benefit the most. 

The rationale for the delegation fees is that because we are maintaining the project, the fees paid to the foundation will be used to **make Bittensor better, smarter, and increase its value**. As opposed to going towards some big delegate's pocket, and maybe sold on some exchange without being actually useful to anyone except the delegate. We hope this also incentivizes delegates to show *where* their stakers funds are going.
